    {
      "step_id": "8115d8dd",
      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Key structural elements**\n- **Polycyclic aromatic/heteroaromatic system:** a fused bicyclic **benzoxazinone-/quinazolinone-like** heteroaromatic core (one **ring N** and one **lactam carbonyl**).\n- **Additional phenyl ring** bearing **Cl** (adds lipophilicity and \u03c0-surface).\n- **Methoxy substituent** on an aromatic ring (H-bond acceptor; modest lipophilicity).\n- **Carboxylate side chain:** `CC(=O)[O-]` is **anionic** at physiological pH (strongly polar, ionized).\n- **No basic amine:** the only nitrogen is **amide-like / ring N** in a lactam/heteroaromatic context, expected **non-basic** (not protonated at pH 7.4).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:53:47.552930+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "703c94f9",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Structural alerts vs hERG**\n- hERG \u201cclassic\u201d pharmacophore often includes a **protonatable basic center** flanked by hydrophobes/aromatics (e.g., terfenadine-like, piperidine + aryl).  \n- This molecule has **aryl hydrophobes**, but **lacks a cationic/basic center** and instead carries a **carboxylate (negative charge)** \u2192 opposite charge profile of many strong hERG blockers.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:53:47.552946+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "c19e26d6",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) REASON about SAR (why these features impact hERG blockade)",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:53:47.552959+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "8e2117bb",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- **Absence of a basic, protonatable nitrogen**: Many high-risk hERG blockers rely on a **cation\u2013\u03c0 / electrostatic interaction** with residues in the channel cavity (notably aromatic residues such as Tyr/Phe and polar residues). Without a cationic center, binding affinity is often substantially reduced.\n- **Presence of a carboxylate (anionic)**: An anion typically **reduces passive membrane partitioning** and **reduces likelihood of reaching/accumulating in the hydrophobic channel cavity**. It can also be electrostatically disfavored in a binding site that often accommodates cationic ligands.\n- **Hydrophobic/aromatic surface still present**: Two aromatic domains (fused heteroaromatic + chlorophenyl) can support \u03c0\u2013\u03c0 interactions, so **some binding is still conceivable**, but usually **not strong** without a basic center.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:53:47.552972+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "8450f6d5",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "Net SAR expectation: **lower hERG risk** than cationic amphiphiles; any blockade would more likely be **weak**.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:53:47.552984+00:00"
    },
    {
